body:
@yunseong Thanks for your insightful comments. I've addressed the following in my next iteration:
1. Return `List<TInput>` on reporting results instead of the list of input-function pairs, since it probably doesn't make sense to aggregate "randomly" (users don't know how which functions Vortex will group together) across functions that do different types of things.
2. Pass back the failed inputs in `VortexAggregateException` such that we can call `onFailure` with it. I wasn't able to make it generic though, would be great if we could type it on `TInput` but `Exception` cannot be made generic :(

@afchung Thanks for the revision! Aggregating results from one function makes sense to me. But wouldn't user want to inspect which function was associated? I'm not 100% sure how user will handle the failed aggregation yet. However, if you plan to add some examples or tests with the failure case in the next PR, I think it is totally fine.

I left some minor comments and I think it is good to be merged after addressing them.
@bgchun Could you kindly take another look at it?

@bgchun @yunseong Thanks for the reviews!

What I meant for aggregating a single function is that the user should just submit `List<TInput>, VortexAggregateFunction, VortexFunction` to `VortexThreadPool` instead of `List<Pair<TInput, VortexFunction>>, VortexAggregateFunction`. I'm not sure if there are many use-cases when the user would want to submit the second type of workload, but everything should just work fine as long as the final aggregation is associative and the groupings can be done arbitrarily. Going with the second API makes constructing the submission objects a lot more verbose and there will be more objects to serialize. With the first API, the user won't need to match the return values to their input-function pair, but only to their input since there is only one single "map" function, so to speak. If the user wants different logic in their function based on their input, the user can always incorporate the different types of logic into a single `VortexFunction` via if-else, although this isn't particularly ideal.

What do you think? Personally I am leaning towards the first API.

@afchung I'm totally +1 on the first API. It seems more cleaner and practical to use.

By the way, there was a comment that was not addressed; I think the argument in `VortexAggregationException` should be the inputs as per the `VortexAggregateFuture`'s signature. 

After you confirm that, I'll merge this. Thanks.
